{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fff7a090-ec3f-4f27-9f44-f7d70ad738c1","content":"You have a few options:\n\n### 1. Use the standalone global tool install (no SDK needed)\nDownload the prebuilt `dotnet-trace` directly:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x dotnet-trace\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID>\n```\n\n### 2. Copy from another image\n```dockerfile\nCOPY --from=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 /usr/share/dotnet /usr/share/dotnet\n```\n…but this is heavy. Option 1 is preferred.\n\n### 3. `docker cp` at runtime\nDownload `dotnet-trace` on the host, then:\n```bash\ndocker cp ./dotnet-trace <container_id>:/tmp/dotnet-trace\ndocker exec <container_id> /tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p 1\n```\n\n**Option 1** is the lightest — it's a self-contained binary with no SDK dependency. Use `--format speedscope` if you want to view the trace in [https://www.speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4bce8b9b-77a1-4c7a-ba68-7f35a18eada4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK. This is a general knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling — I don't need to search the codebase for this.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":366},"id":"4d9dfce5-e6b9-4628-8605-5c25faf9c205","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:46.458Z","parentId":"7340ed2d-2cf4-4e33-8764-363cd4cf414c"}
